An Osun State Magistrates’ Court sitting in Ile-Ife on Thursday, remanded 25-year-old Oyeniyi Oluwasegun, for allegedly forging Obafemi Awolowo University (OAU) certificate to facilitate internet fraud. He however, pleaded not guilty to four – count charge of forgery, impersonation, illegal signature and usage of public seal slammed on him. The police prosecutor, Inspector Sunday Osanyintuyi, told the court that the defendant committed the offence on Jan 20, 2019 around 1:00 pm at Iloromu Area, Ile-Ife. Osanyintuyi said that Oyeniyi Oluwasegun unlawfully forged Obafemi Awolowo University certificate to facilitate internet scandal. He added that the defendant also impersonate himself as Dean,  Faculty of Science, Obafemi Awolowo University, Ile-Ife, by presenting to the Police a forged document. According to him, the defendant assumed the power of dean of Faculty of Science of Obafemi Awolowo University, Ile-Ife, by affixing his signature to authenticate a forged certificate that bear OAU. The Prosecutor stated further that the defendant used public seal bearing Obafemi Awolowo University, Ile-Ife in a forged document prepared for illegal act. He said that the offence contravened sections 107(2), 108(2) and 467(1) (2) of the Criminal Code, Laws of Osun, 2002. The Defence Counsel, Mr Martins Awe, pleaded for the bail of the defendant in most liberal term with the promise that his client would not jump bail, but provide substantial sureties and stand his case. Magistrate Joseph Owolawi, did not grant the bail of the defendant, but ordered for his remand in Ile-Ife Correctional Centre as he adjourned the case until Jan 30, for ruling on bail. 